    {
      "title": "Diphthongs and triphthongs",
      "html": "<p>A <b>diphthong</b> is a vowel sound that glides from one vowel quality to another in the same syllable. RP English has 8 diphthongs:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>/eɪ/ — <i>day, name, wait</i></li>\n    <li>/aɪ/ — <i>my, high, buy</i></li>\n    <li>/ɔɪ/ — <i>boy, toy, coin</i></li>\n    <li>/əʊ/ — <i>go, boat, no</i></li>\n    <li>/aʊ/ — <i>now, house, cow</i></li>\n    <li>/ɪə/ — <i>near, here, dear</i></li>\n    <li>/eə/ — <i>hair, care, there</i></li>\n    <li>/ʊə/ — <i>tour, poor</i></li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>A <b>triphthong</b> glides through three vowel qualities in a single syllable: <i>fire</i> /faɪə/, <i>hour</i> /aʊə/, <i>player</i> /pleɪə/, <i>royal</i> /rɔɪəl/, <i>lower</i> /ləʊə/.</p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "State the diphthong in <i>coin</i>.",
          "a": "/ɔɪ/."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Consonant clusters",
      "html": "<p>A <b>consonant cluster</b> is a group of two or more consonants next to each other without a vowel between them, at the beginning or end of a syllable.</p>\n  <h4>Initial clusters</h4>\n  <ul><li>2-consonant: <i>play, snow, cry, glass, twin, dwell</i>.</li>\n  <li>3-consonant: <i>splash, string, scream, spread</i> — always begins with /s/, then /p, t, k/, then /l, r, w, j/.</li></ul>\n  <h4>Final clusters</h4>\n  <ul><li>2 consonants: <i>help, hand, jump, best</i>.</li>\n  <li>3 consonants: <i>text /tekst/, next /nekst/, sixths /sɪksθs/</i>.</li></ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Identify the initial cluster in <i>spring</i>.",
          "a": "/spr/."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Intonation and emphatic stress",
      "html": "<p><b>Intonation</b> is the rise and fall of the voice in speech. Two main tunes:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><b>Falling tune (⇘)</b> — used for statements, commands, WH-questions, exclamations: <i>I am tired.⇘ Where is he?⇘</i></li>\n    <li><b>Rising tune (⇗)</b> — used for yes/no questions, polite requests, incomplete lists: <i>Are you coming?⇗ Would you like tea?⇗</i></li>\n  </ul>\n  <p><b>Emphatic (or contrastive) stress</b> puts extra stress on a particular word to change the meaning of a sentence:</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li><b>I</b> gave her the book — <i>(I did, not somebody else)</i></li>\n    <li>I gave her the <b>book</b> — <i>(not the pen)</i></li>\n    <li>I gave <b>her</b> the book — <i>(not him)</i></li>\n  </ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Which tune is used for a yes/no question?",
          "a": "Rising tune (⇗)."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
